[normal]Minimising disruption in the first place[bold]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]In recent years th
[normal]ere have been a number of initiatives to ensure that the railway is less 
[normal]susceptible
[normal] to snow and ice than it has been in the past, some led by train operators and some by Network Rail.  
[normal]For 
[normal]example, m
[normal]odifications to prevent snow damaging electric traction motor
[normal]s and heating the third rail at key locations to prevent icing
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal]              
[normal]It is impossible for Passenger Focus to judge w
[normal]hether what has been delivered so far
[normal] 
[normal]is sufficien
[normal]t.  However, 
[normal]it is 
[normal]worth noting that train performance
[normal] (as measured by the Public Performance Measure) 
[normal]in winter 2012/13 was worse than 2011/12 – 
[normal]although 
[normal]factors
[normal] other than the weather may have been involved.
[normal] 
[normal] We 
[normal]therefore 
[normal]support the Office of Rail Regulation’s requirement
[normal] for robust weather resilience proposals in Network Rail’s Control Period 5 (2014-19) Delivery Plan.
