[normal]Passenger Focus research
[normal] suggests that various factors 
[normal]contribute to how passengers rate the handling of disruption
[normal], including
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]7
[normal]              
[normal]I
[normal]nformation at times of disruption 
[normal]is heading 
[normal]slowly in the right direction
[normal].  Many more train companies now have ‘rainbow boards’ on their websites giving ‘at 
[normal]a glance’ status of the service
[normal]; p
[normal]assengers
[normal] following most train companies on Twitter 
[normal]receive 
[normal]marked
[normal]ly better information than in the past
[normal]; and it is now possible for pre-prepared ‘snow timetables’ to show through electronic journey planners the evening before
[normal].  
[normal]However, 
[normal]we continue to see inaccur
[normal]acies, inconsistencies and ambiguities at times of disruption, whether the cause 
[normal]is winter weather 
[normal]or not.
[normal]  A 
[normal]remaining 
[normal]weakness is the 
[normal]in
[normal]ability to give an accurate estimate of how long 
[normal]a disruption will last, 
[normal]even some hours into an incident, let alone 
[normal]an indication of how long knock
[normal]-
[normal]on delays will continue to affect journeys.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]8
[normal]              
[normal]Information.[bold]  
[normal]After observations over winter 2012/13, Passenger Focus 
[normal]highlighted 
[normal]– via the 
[normal]rail industry’s 
[normal]National Taskforce – 
[normal]four areas of continuing weakness
[normal] in informati
[normal]on provision during disruption
[normal]:
[normal]as
[normal] necessary
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]9
[normal]              
[normal]Empathy and practical action.[bold]  
[normal]The tendency of train companies to
[normal] sometimes
[normal] give the impression 
[normal]t
[normal]hat they do not “treat me with respect
[normal] [as a paying customer]” is a particular problem at times of service disruptio
[normal]n, whether caused by 
[normal]winter 
[normal]weather 
[normal]or anything else.  
[normal]Passengers also get the impression that the 
[normal]rail 
[normal]industry can be slow with practical action
[normal] to minimise th
[normal]eir inconvenience
[normal].  
[normal]Passenger Focus continues to highlight specific areas that contribute to th
[normal]ese
[normal] impression
[normal]s
[normal], including:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1
[normal]0
[normal]              
[normal]Welfare of passengers.[bold]  
[normal]Occasionally, 
[normal]the way 
[normal]disruption 
[normal]is handled g
[normal]ets close to the line between 
[normal]poor 
[normal]customer service and failure to safeguard the welfare of passengers.
[normal]  Incidents at Kings Cross on 19 February (200 passengers forced to ‘sleep’ overnight on a train in the station
[normal]; at Virginia Water on 9 May (passengers arrived home 
[normal]around midnight h
[normal]aving left Waterloo at 1720 
[normal]after a tree fell across the railway); and at 
[normal]Pewsey
[normal] on 4 August
[normal] (Penzance to Paddington train 
[normal]stuck for 5 hours).  
[normal]Incident reviews often find a culture of “don’t worry, this problem will sort itself out in half an hour”, with 
[normal]no
[normal] parallel
[normal] “but what
[normal] about the passengers 
[normal]if it doesn’t
[normal]?”  
[normal]Since the Kings Cross incident, Passenger Focus has written to all train companies about late-night service 
[normal]disruption,
[normal] and most have replied that their arrangements would have prevented a similar
[normal] incident.  
[normal]Nevertheless
[normal],
[normal] incidents keep 
[normal]happening
[normal] which, if they had coincided with extreme winter weather (or extreme heat)
[normal],
[normal] could have led to serious 
[normal]passenger 
[normal]welfare issues.
[normal]2.
[normal]11
[normal]              
[normal]Information needs – extreme weather.  [bold]Passengers’ information requirements during disruption caused by winter weather are largely the same as during any other disruption.  However, when snow has 
[normal]fallen
[normal] passengers have an extra requirement – because they have reason to suspect that trains 
[normal]may
[normal] b
[normal]e affected.  Train companies still have more to do to help passengers answer th
[normal]e
[normal] initial “can I get there?” question when 
[normal]they 
[normal]open their curtains to snow, or hear about it on the radio.  This is as much about reassurance that all 
[normal]is
[normal] 
[normal]well
[normal] as it
[normal] is about wa
[normal]rning of disruption.  For commuters, the question “and will I get home again
[normal]?
[normal]” will also be in their mind.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]1
[normal]2
[normal]              
[normal]‘snow [bold]timetables[bold]’[bold] – commuter networks[bold].[bold]  Passenger Focus is in principle persuaded by the argument 
[normal]that
[normal],
[normal] faced with a horrendous weather forecast
[normal] it is in 
[normal]passengers’ interests if commuter train 
[normal]companies 
[normal]run a timetable 
[normal]they are 
[normal]confident can be 
[normal]delivered 
[normal]despite the weather.
[normal]  Attempting to deliver the impossible and failing spectacularly does not help
[normal] anybody
[normal].  
[normal]With effective communications it should be possible 
[normal]for train companies 
[normal]to get the message to commuters that a ‘snow timetable’ will run tomorrow, with full details of what that means made available quickly
[normal].  However, ‘snow timetables’ must
[normal] 
[normal]stil
[normal]l 
[normal]meet the needs of passengers
[normal] – 
[normal]in
[normal] 
[normal]terms of continuing to run trains from all stations 
[normal]wherever p
[normal]ossible and providing 
[normal]enou
[normal]g
[normal]h coaches 
[normal]that 
[normal]pass
[normal]engers do not get left behind.  Passenger Focus felt that South West Trains did not 
[normal]quite 
[normal]get this right when th
[normal]ey implemented a ‘snow timetable’ in January 2013 and they have undertaken to review arrangements for the coming winter.
[normal]  
[normal]T
[normal]here is always 
[normal]the potential 
[normal]that the 
[normal]forecast snow does not materialise and 
[normal]passengers conclud
[normal]e 
[normal]that the train company has redu
[normal]ced t
[normal]he service unnecessarily.  To reduce th
[normal]at
[normal] risk, the time by which 
[normal]it 
[normal]must 
[normal]be 
[normal]decide
[normal]d
[normal] whether to run a ‘snow timetable’ the 
[normal]next 
[normal]day should be 
[normal]a
[normal]s late as possible, while still allowing the revised 
[normal]times 
[normal]to show 
[normal]in 
[normal]journey planning systems that evening.  The
[normal] industry should also enhance its capability to restore the normal timetable, or elements of 
[normal]it,
[normal] if it becomes clear the ‘snow timetable’ is not needed.
[normal]  
[normal]              
[normal]2.1
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]‘snow timetables’ – long-distance operators.[bold]  In contrast, Passenger Focus supports the position taken by some long-distance operators, e.g. 
[normal]CrossCountry
[normal] and Virgin Trains,
[normal] 
[normal]that the fu
[normal]ll timetable 
[normal]should be maintained 
[normal]wherever possible.  Infrequent, long-distance passengers are m
[normal]ore difficult to war
[normal]n 
[normal]that a different timetable will be in operation
[normal], and 
[normal]retiming the 11
[normal]:
[normal]00 to 11
[normal]:
[normal]08
[normal], for example,
[normal] would cause considerable confusion – not least to those whose ticket is for the 11
[normal]:
[normal]00 and no other train.  
[normal]Re-writing the timetable with fewer trai
[normal]ns taking lo
[normal]nger than normal also risks the (reasonable) accusation that it has been done not in passengers’ interests
[normal],
[normal] but purely to boost punctuality statistics.
