[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.[bold]              [bold]Bus p[bold]assenger[bold]s’[bold] attitudes and priorities [bold]&#xa0;[bold]3. 1
[normal]              
[normal]While b
[normal]us passengers would
[normal] 
[normal]clearly 
[normal]rather there is 
[normal]no disruption in the first place
[normal], they recognise that bus services will inevitably be impacted when significant snow 
[normal]and/or 
[normal]ice affects the road network.  Nevertheless, bus passengers do expect that reasonable steps 
[normal]will be 
[normal]taken to ensure that buses conti
[normal]nue to run
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]and as reliably as 
[normal]possible, 
[normal]wherever
[normal] it is safe to do so.  
[normal]Whether 
[normal]pressure on 
[normal]local authority 
[normal]2013/14 
[normal]b
[normal]udgets
[normal] will reduce the priority 
[normal]a
[normal]ttach
[normal]ed
[normal] to gritting principal bus routes
[normal]/ 
[normal]a
[normal]ccess to
[normal] bus garages this winter remains to be seen.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. 3
[normal]              
[normal]Passenger Focus published research 
[normal]earlier in 
[normal]2013 
[normal]looking at 
[normal]bus passengers’ experiences of delays and service disruption
[normal].  Although covering experiences 
[normal]of delays 
[normal]resulting from many different causes, i.e. not just severe winter weather, 
[normal]a number of 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]findings 
[normal]and recommendations 
[normal]are relevant to this 
[normal]Inquiry
[normal].  The research found that improvements in two key areas would 
[normal]change
[normal] passengers’ experiences during disruption 
[normal]– information and driver attitude.  Passengers spoke about feeling 
[normal]‘
[normal]powerless
[normal]’
[normal] standin
[normal]g at a bus stop not knowing if a bus will come – as one 
[normal]research respondent 
[normal]put it “it’s mental torture sometimes at bus stops working out whether to stay or whether to go”.  Passengers also said they wanted bus drivers to 
[normal]behave more as the bus company’s 
[normal]customer service representative, providing information, showing empathy and expressing regret.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. 4
[normal]              
[normal]Passenger Focus’s recommendations in the light of this research include:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. 
[normal]5
[normal]              
[normal]If
[normal] there is disruption 
[normal]to bus services 
[normal]caused by severe 
[normal]winter 
[normal]weather, good in
[normal]formation is key to minimising the impact on passengers.  
[normal]I
[normal]nformation 
[normal]that allows passengers to m
[normal]ake an informed decision – be it 
[normal]to 
[normal]set out earlier, 
[normal]not 
[normal]attempt to travel, find a different way to get there – 
[normal]should b
[normal]e a key 
[normal]objective 
[normal]for 
[normal]bus companies and
[normal]/or local authorities.
[normal]  Providing assurance that buses 
[normal]are
[normal] running, if potentially with delays, is important as well: when it has snowed passengers have reason to doubt it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]Rail.  
[normal]The NPS shows that for rail passengers the way disruption is managed is moving slowly in the right direction, but there 
[normal]remains 
[normal]a considerable way to go.
[normal]  It is important to ask what more could be done to improve the railway’s resilience to snow and ice.  
[normal]When 
[normal]disruption 
[normal]occurs
[normal] 
[normal]information that allows passengers to make an informed choice about what they do is vital.  D
[normal]u
[normal]ring 
[normal]winter 2012/13 
[normal]passenger information 
[normal]was better, but it was 
[normal]far from 
[normal]perf
[normal]ect
[normal] and t
[normal]his 
[normal]paper 
[normal]mentions a number of areas in which furthe
[normal]r improvement is needed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]Bus.  When bus services are disrupted, for any reason, passengers’ key requirement is for information about what is going on – and yet many feel
[normal] 
[normal]there is no effective means to find 
[normal]that 
[normal]out
[normal].  How would a passenger working in their office find out that a bus company had decided it would suspend operations at 16:00 
[normal]because heavy snow is 
[normal]forecast?   In some cases 
[normal]it
[normal] is true
[normal]:
[normal] without a system tracking the location of buses in 
[normal]real-time
[normal], there is
[normal] no means to find out exactly what is happening – but in other
[normal]s 
[normal]Apps 
[normal]exist, 
[normal]but few passengers appear to know about them.  A quick win for the bus industry would be to raise awareness about Apps and other sources of information where reliable 
[normal]real-time
[normal] sys
[normal]tems are in place.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]              
[normal]How public transport operators manage service disruption, including that caused by severe winter weather remains an important area 
[normal]of work 
[normal]for Passenger Focus.  If snow and ice causes disruption this winter we will monitor how well 
[normal]train and bus companies cope, including in the vital area of passenger information.
